## Important Notes for Implementation

1. **Index alignment between df and bins**: `bins` is indexed by the event
   t0 timestamps from `run_labels`. Not every row of `df` will have a label
   (some may have been dropped by `minRet` or `dropLabels`). When slicing
   features for the CV loop, always align via `bins.index` intersection
   with `df.index`, not by positional indexing.

2. **The `t1` Series**: this is the critical object that connects labeling
   to CV. It maps each event's start time (t0) to its barrier-touch time
   (t1). Both `PurgedKFold` and `CombinatorialPurgedKFold` require it to
   know which training observations overlap with the test set.

3. **`Raw_Close` usage**: the labels module needs `Raw_Close` (untransformed
   prices) for barrier calculations. After labeling is complete, `Raw_Close`
   is no longer needed as a feature. It should be excluded from any feature
   matrix passed to models. The `feature_metadata` dict already excludes
   raw OHLCV columns, so filtering features by `list(feature_metadata.keys())`
   is the safe pattern.

4. **SADF/SMT computation time**: the econometrics block computes O(n³)
   SADF and SMT signals. On ~4000 daily observations this takes 1–3 minutes.
   Add a print statement before and after with elapsed time so the user
   knows the notebook hasn't hung.

5. **Saving convention**: every block that transforms data saves its output
   to `data/interim/` so that the notebook can be restarted from any block
   by loading the previous block's saved artefacts. Include a commented-out
   "load from checkpoint" cell at the top of each block for this purpose.

